05052nam a22006495i 9780691194615DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191993nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911946157 a10.1515/97806911946152doi  a(DE-B1597)515929  a(OCoLC)1077292154  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDG738.14.M2 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a320.1/0922231 aNajemy, John M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Friends :bDiscourses of Power and Desire in the Machiavelli-Vettori Letters of 1513-1515 /cJohn M. Najemy. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Legacy Library ;v527400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION: The Letters in Machiavelli Studies -- tCHAPTER ONE: Renaissance Epistolarity -- tCHAPTER TWO: Contexts Personal and Political -- tCHAPTER THREE: "Formerly Secretary" -- tCHAPTER FOUR: Speaking like Romans -- tCHAPTER FIVE : The Prince "Addressed" to Francesco Vettori -- tCHAPTER SIX: Geta and the "Antiqui Huomini" (The Letter of 10 December 1513) -- tCHAPTER SEVEN: "A Ridiculous Metamorphosis" -- tCHAPTER EIGHT: "After a Thousand Years" -- tCHAPTER NINE: Poetry and Politic -- tEPILOGUE: The Poets of the Discourses -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween Friends offers the first extended close reading of the most famous epistolary dialogue of the Renaissance, the letters exchanged from 1513 to 1515 by Niccolo Machiavelli and Francesco Vettori. John Najemy reveals the literary richness and theoretical tensions of the correspondence, the crucial importance of the dialogue with Vettori in Machiavelli's emergence as a writer and political theorist, and the close but complex relationship between the letters and Machiavelli's major works on politics. Unlike previous and mostly fragmentary treatments of the correspondence, this book reads the letters as a continuously developing, collaborative text in which problems of language and interpretation gradually emerge as the critical issues.Najemy argues that Vettori's skeptical reaction to Machiavelli's first letters on politics and provoked Machiavelli into a defense of language's power to represent the world, a notion that soon become the underlying assumption of The Prince. Later, and largely through an apparently whimsical exchange of letters on love and the foibles of eros, Vettori led Machiavelli to confront the power of desire in language, which opened the way for a different, essentially poetic, approach to writing about politics that surfaces for the first time in the pages of the Discourses on Livy.John M. Najemy is Professor of History at Cornell University. He is the author of Corporatism and Consensus in Florentine Electoral Politics, 1280-1400 (North Carolina).Originally published in 1993.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691194615zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps